mxCell.value: Start State: One start state to a module; one outgoing arc allowed.  Make sure to change the module from legend to whatever you are creating.
Decision State: Used to make decisions about  where to proceed depending upon the value of the variable.
Stop State: No outgoing arc allowed.  Returns control to the calling state (or stops). Make sure to change the module from legend to whatever you are creating.

Prompt State: One outgoing arc allowed.  The default prompt state has one prompt, but you can add as many as you want in the properties list, using the format Prompt_N_Name - Prompt_N_Text where the prompts are rendered in ascending N order.

To see an object's property list, hover over the object with your mouse.  To edit the list or to add your own properties, select on the object, then from the top menu select Edit > Edit Data to see/edit the properties list of key-value pairs.

mxCell.value: Grammar State: Labels on the outgoing arcs represent the user's semantic intent.  Prompts follow the same conventions as discussed in the prompt state above. Add as many grammars as required.  The default list has 2, a state-specific grammar (e.g., YNQ) and a global grammar (e.g. Global).  Follow the same convention as prompts for additional grammars. Create a grammar object (see below for examples) for every grammar mentioned in the properties list.  The slot name is the field name in a grammar which is populated with a value in the user's response.

Computational State: Used to set variables to values. In this example, it is setting the variable named feelings to have the value good.  These variables and values can be checked by other states, such as a Decision State (see below).

object.Meaning_2_Words: start over, restart, go back to the beginning

mxCell.value: Sub Dialog: Refers to a separate graph usually existing in another module on a different page.  It should have a start state and a return state.  By convention, if a Sub Dialog has an exit arc, it acts like a subroutine with a return state.  If the Sub Dialog symbol does not have a exiting arc, than treat it as a labelled Go Sub.

Grammar: Specify the module and the possible responses. The first item becomes the semantic intent. The grammar named Global has some special treatment in that if there are two grammars at a state and one of them is named Global, and both grammars have the same terms (i.e., the response from the user is ambiguous) then the default application behavior is to follow the global grammar.
Global Behavior: Specify things like global error messages, retry's, timeouts, etc.
